The paper deals with polynomial identity testing, hitting-set generators, and lower bounds for various models of computation, which are all topics in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of algebraic geometry and the Jacobian is a central theme in the paper, which suggests that it could also be relevant to computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also involves the study of circuits and formulas, which are common objects of study in discrete mathematics (cs.DS). The connection between identity testing and lower bounds is another important aspect of the paper, which could make it relevant to both computational complexity theory and computational geometry (cs.SC). Finally, the paper involves the study of transcendence degree, which is a concept from algebraic geometry and number theory, and could make it relevant to algebraic geometry and topology (cs.GT).
